VAX MANDATE OVERTURNED IN NYC

The New York Supreme Court overturned what it called an "arbitrary and capricious" Covid-19 vaccine mandate for New York City employees. 

In their ruling, the court reinstated all employees who had been fired for not being vaccinated and ordered they be given back pay.

Back up: Earlier this year, NYC Mayor Eric Adams [Democrat] fired roughly 2,000 city workers including police, teachers, and firemen over their refusal to get the Covid vaccine.

NY Supreme Court Justice Ralph Porzio pointed out how Mayor Adams was picking favorites by lifting the mandate for artists and athletes, but not for city workers:

‚ÄúThere is nothing in the record to support the rationality of keeping a vaccination mandate for public employees while vacating the mandate for private sector employees or creating a carveout for certain professions, like artists, athletes or performers."

‚ÄúThis is clearly and arbitrary and capricious action because we are dealing with identical unvaccinated people being treated differently by the same administrative agency.‚Äù

This judge seems like a really solid guy. He also added:

"The vaccination mandate for [New York] City employees was not just about safety and public health; it was about compliance."

The Democrat regime in NY plans to appeal the judge's ruling, saying they ‚Äústrongly disagrees with this ruling as the mandate is firmly grounded in law and is critical to New Yorkers‚Äô public health.‚Äù

[Source: AP, Daily Wire]

Allein in New York City wurden Anfang des Jahres rund 1.400 Mitarbeiter entlassen, weil sie nicht geimpft waren, nachdem die Stadt unter dem fr√ºheren B√ºrgermeister Bill de Blasio eine Impfpflicht eingef√ºhrt hatte.

Prussian Socialism Episode 20: The Teutonic Knights and Germanic Holy War [featuring Warren Balogh]

Everyone knows about the Crusades in the Holy Land. But what about the Crusades in the Baltic? For 300 years, the Teutonic Order waged war across the Baltic, Poland and even Russia to bring Christianity to the last Pagan peoples in Europe.

The Order was founded in Acre in 1190. After a brief stay in Transylvania, it found its calling in the swampy forests on the north-eastern edge of civilization. Under its Grandmaster Hermann von Salza, the Order established a military mini-state devoted to holy war. Trudging though snow and frost, its heavily armed knights and swarms of crossbowmen raided villages, built castles, and brought Christianity to the heathen. 

Germans, Poles, Russians, and everyone else have often depicted the Northern Crusades as violent‚Äîyet glorious‚Äîrace-wars. On the other hand, many modern historians have downplayed this interpretation. Who is right? Were the Teutonic Knights evil predators, noble holy-warriors, or something else entirely? Gregory Conte and Warren Balogh explore this dark and nearly forgotten chapter of European history.

William Urban. The Teutonic Knights a Military History (a dry but straight forward overview)
Eric Christianson. The Northern Crusades (a rather tedious academic study)
